article.description:
Tracy McGrady scored 23 of his 39 
points in the third quarter as the Orlando Magic rolled past the
hapless Cleveland Cavaliers, 109-85, for their third straight
win.
article.headline: McGrady scores 23 of his 39 in third quarter
article.linkText: McGrady carries Magic 'parasites' past Cavs, toward playoffs
article.story:
ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Cleveland Cavaliers coach Keith Smart considers Tracy McGrady a special player who makes his Orlando Magic teammates better.
McGrady

McGrady scored 39 points in 30 minutes and watched from the bench during the fourth quarter as the Magic completed a four-game sweep of the Cavaliers with a 109-85 victory Friday night. "I use the word lightly -- 'parasites,''' Smart said of the rest of the Magic players. "They feed off his greatness and take advantage of little things. I'm not saying in any way these guys are bad players. They just feed off McGrady and it's enhancing what they do.'' McGrady, who scored 133 points in the four victories over Cleveland, scored 30 or more points for the 42nd time this season. He tied a team record with eight consecutive 30-plus games, and extended his franchise mark to 39 games in a row with 20 or more. His performance even caught coach Doc Rivers by surprise. "The last I looked was in the second quarter and he had 11,'' Rivers said of McGrady. "Right before I took him out, I glanced at the board and I saw 39. I don't know where it came from. Obviously, the third quarter, but I was clueless as to what he was doing.'' McGrady is keeping Orlando alive in the playoff race as the No. 7 seed in the East with 13 games remaining. He isn't focused on the teams ahead of the Magic, just the goal. "We're not playing anyone,'' Rivers said. "We're playing to try to get to the playoffs. Our opponent is the playoffs. Everyone's an obstacle. Cleveland's in your way tonight, Miami will be in your way on Sunday night. That has helped our basketball team, not to look at who we're playing.'' Milt Palacio scored 15 points to lead the Cavaliers, who have lost 10 of their last 11. The third quarter ended with McGrady making a spectacular reverse layup to reach 39 points. He had 23 in the quarter on 6-of-10 shooting and was 9-for-10 at the line. With the Magic ahead 84-64, McGrady watched the fourth quarter from the bench. He was 12-of-21 from the field and 12-of-13 from the free-throw line. "I'm just in a great rhythm right now, playing at a high level, trying to maintain for the rest of the season,'' McGrady said. Darrell Armstrong added 14 points for the Magic, and Gordan Giricek and Andrew DeClercq had nine each. The Magic played without Drew Gooden, who sat out with a sprained right big toe. Gooden was injured in the Magic's game against Miami on Wednesday and is day-to-day. Cleveland shot 45.7 percent and placed five players in double figures, including Palacio, Zydrunas Ilgauskas (13), Ricky Davis (12), Jumaine Jones (12) and Chris Mihm (11). The Cavaliers committed 23 turnovers in losing for the 10th time in 11 games. "It was our mistakes of turning the ball over and them playing their game,'' Smart said. "We gave up 20 steals, and those aren't your normal turnovers because you can't guard a steal. They're playing for a purpose of keeping their position in the playoff hunt or moving up, so that's what they're trying to establish.'' Orlando pulled away early in the third quarter when McGrady followed a three-point play with back-to-back 3-pointers to put the Magic ahead 63-44 at 9:24. Orlando led by at least 12 points the entire quarter. McGrady had 16 at the half to put Orlando ahead 52-40. The Magic scored 14 points off 13 Cleveland turnovers. Ilgauskas was 5-of-6 from the field to lead Cleveland with 12 points. Orlando stayed in the lead for good after Giricek's 3-pointer put the Magic ahead 19-16 with 5:12 remaining in the first quarter.

Game notes
Cleveland's Dajuan Wagner was not with the team after undergoing season-ending arthroscopic knee surgery on Friday. ... Garrity had a career-high five steals. ... Orlando has won 11 of its last 14 against Cleveland. ... The Magic outscored the Cavaliers 48-32 in the paint. ... Cleveland was 18-for-28 at the line.
